"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:1.3.1.3\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">1.3.1.3</span> Net, trammel net</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מָצוֹד</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(matsod (see also )</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job19:6\">JOB 19:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eccl7:26\">ECC 7:26</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מְצוֹדָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mtsodah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eccl9:12\">ECC 9:12</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">δίκτυον</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(diktuon)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt4:20\">MAT 4:20</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt4:21\">MAT 4:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:18\">MRK 1:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:19\">MRK 1:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke5:2\">LUK 5:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke5:4\">LUK 5:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke5:5\">LUK 5:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke5:6\">LUK 5:6</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0336_trammel_net.png\" alt=\"Fish in a trammel net\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Fish in a trammel net (Lindsay G. Thompson, University of Washington, CC0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>The trammel net was actually two or three nets combined in layers, usually a small-mesh inner net sandwiched between two nets of looser mesh.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>Similar to the dragnet, the trammel net was set out vertically in the water, held in place by floats on the surface of the water and weighted down by a single weighted rope at the bottom. Fish swam through the outer layer and into the fine-mesh net (1), pushing it through the other layer of loose mesh (2). This caught the fish in a kind of pocket from which they could not return (3). Unlike the dragnet, which was drawn in immediately after it was spread out, the trammel net was left in place for several hours to give time for fish to accumulate in it.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The Hebrew words <em>matsod</em> and <em>mtsodah</em> probably refer to “net” in a generic sense, whether for fishing or for hunting.</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt4:20\">MAT 4:20</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt4:21\">MAT 4:21</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:18\">MRK 1:18</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:19\">MRK 1:19</a>; and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke5:2\">LUK 5:2</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke5:4\">LUK 5:4</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke5:5\">LUK 5:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke5:6\">LUK 5:6</a>, it is possible that the Greek word <em>diktuon</em> refers to the dragnet (1.3.1.2), although the plural “nets” makes it likely that a trammel net is meant since it alone was made up of multiple nets. A generic term for “net” may be used in languages that do not require that a distinction be made.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
